From: <Richard Stallman>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Subject: Boeing and Spirit AeroSystems
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit
Content-Base: https://stallman.org/archives/2024-may-aug.html#4_July_2024_(Boeing_and_Spirit_AeroSystems)
Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Boeing and Spirit AeroSystems</title>
    <base href="https://stallman.org/archives/2024-may-aug.html#4_July_2024_(Boeing_and_Spirit_AeroSystems)">
  </head>
  <body id="msgFeedSummaryBody" selected="false">
    <p>
Boeing has been pressured by the US government to <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/article/2024/jul/01/boeing-to-buy-supplier-spirit-aerosystems-deal">buy the part of
Spirit AeroSystems</a> that makes parts for Boeing planes -- a part that
it spun off a few decades ago.
<p>
Spinning off parts or aspects of production is effective for
increasing profits -- by paying some workers less, and by shirking
accountability for whatever goes wrong.  Except that when what goes
wrong is that a plane crashes, the responsibility bounces back.
<p>
I would expect the previous management of Boeing viewed making their
parts in-house as a way to make their planes safer.  So it always
comes back to one's values.

<p>
  </body>
</html>


